05031nam a22006735i 9781400840779DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20112003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008407797 a10.1515/97814008407792doi  a(DE-B1597)446810  a(OCoLC)979593680  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHD3616 .I42 C45 2008 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a338.0954/09/0451 aChibber, Vivek, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLocked in Place :bState-Building and Late Industrialization in India /cVivek Chibber.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b8 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPART I. The Issues and the Argument -- tCHAPTER 1. Introduction -- tCHAPTER 2. Late Development and State-Building -- tPART II. Installing the State -- tCHAPTER 3. The Origins of the Developmental State in Korea -- tCHAPTER 4. Precursors to Planning in India: The Myth of the Developmental Bourgeoisie -- tCHAPTER 5. The Demobilization of the Labor Movement -- tCHAPTER 6. The Business Offensive and the Retreat of the State -- tPART III. Reproducing the State -- tCHAPTER 7. State Structure and Industrial Policy -- tCHAPTER 8. Locked in Place: Explaining the Non-Occurrence of Reform -- tCHAPTER 9. Conclusion -- tEPILOGUE. The Decline of Development Models -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy were some countries able to build "developmental states" in the decades after World War II while others were not? Through a richly detailed examination of India's experience, Locked in Place argues that the critical factor was the reaction of domestic capitalists to the state-building project. During the 1950s and 1960s, India launched an extremely ambitious and highly regarded program of state-led development. But it soon became clear that the Indian state lacked the institutional capacity to carry out rapid industrialization. Drawing on newly available archival sources, Vivek Chibber mounts a forceful challenge to conventional arguments by showing that the insufficient state capacity stemmed mainly from Indian industrialists' massive campaign, in the years after Independence, against a strong developmental state. Chibber contrasts India's experience with the success of a similar program of state-building in South Korea, where political elites managed to harness domestic capitalists to their agenda. He then develops a theory of the structural conditions that can account for the different reactions of Indian and Korean capitalists as rational responses to the distinct development models adopted in each country. Provocative and marked by clarity of prose, this book is also the first historical study of India's post-colonial industrial strategy. Emphasizing the central role of capital in the state-building process, and restoring class analysis to the core of the political economy of development, Locked in Place is an innovative work of theoretical power that will interest development specialists, political scientists, and historians of the subcontinent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140084077940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400840779423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400840779.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2 